@petehunt @sebmarkbage I've had a number of people ask this on IRC now, and I'm not really sure what the answer is myself. But the current situation seems illogical to me:

``` JS
// key OK, ref OK
<div><Item key="a" ref="a" />

// key OK, ref OK
<div><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

``` JS
// key OK/ERR (possibly unexpected conflicts), ref is OK
<PlainList><Item key="a" ref="a" />

// key OK (may conflict), ref is OK
<PlainList><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

``` JS
// key OK, ref OK
<WrappedPlainList><Item key="a" ref="a" />

// key OK, ref OK
<WrappedPlainList><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

``` JS
// key ERR (discarded), ref ERR (discarded)
<CloneWithPropsList><Item key="a" ref="a" />

// cloneWithProps ERR (does not support arrays/objects)
<CloneWithPropsList><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

``` JS
// key OK, ref OK
<WrappedCloneWithPropsList><Item key="a" ref="a" />

// key OK, ref OK
<WrappedCloneWithPropsList><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

``` JS
// key ERR (discarded), ref ERR (discarded)
<ForEachCloneWithPropsList><Item key="a" ref="a" /><Item key="b" ref="b" />...
```

I would expect them all to work like `<PlainList>` (I think?). Or perhaps even more preferable, like `<WrappedPlainList>`. `<Wrapped*` is implemented as `children = <div>{this.props.children}</div>`, so `cloneWithProps` won't actually add props to the children as-is, but imagine that it did.

Am I missing something? Because the current situation seems fundamentally plain broken to me, using `this.props.children` as-is is dangerous and `cloneWithProps` destroys ownership.

I do understand that it's because of the change of ownership to the local instance, but what's the intended use-case for this behavior? But I'm not 100% sure what the expected behavior would be either... but it seems like keys should concatenate and all refs should be kept (i.e, multiple owners).

Related #1867 #1274
